oakcurric:unit-2671
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and Create: creating melodic variations based on a theme"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-creating-melodic-variations-based-on-a-theme" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will compose short variations on a given simple theme using
  glockenspiels or online keyboards on tablets or laptops. Exploring examples of theme and
  variations such as 'The Young Person's Guide to the Orchestra' will create an
  understanding of how this structure is formed."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit is a culmination of all compositing skills learnt during key
  stages 1 and 2. The pupils bring to this their knowledge of tonality, including major, minor,
  pentatonic and a set raag. They understand music can be structured and have used structures
  including call and response and ternary for example. They understand various ways to notate
  music including rhythm grids and simplified staves. They are now able to explore the creation
  of variations using all their musical knowledge and skills to date.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2671-8 ;
  curric:id "2671"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.119042Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-music-over-time-and-in-different-places ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2664
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Playing together: discovering different vocal timbres"@en ;
  curric:slug "playing-together-polyrhythms-as-part-of-an-ensemble" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces beatboxing as a vocal art form. The sounds of the drum
  machine are recreated using vocal percussion alongside other beatboxing influences
  including the sounds of nature. Working in groups, pupils build texture with multilayered
  vocal sounds."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit brings together an understanding of pulse, rhythm, texture and
  vocal timbre. Through the addition of beatboxing, pupils further develop their ability to
  keep in time when performing in parts through this new style. By this stage, the pupils have
  an awareness of their vocal health, the need to warm up effectively, and how to stand for
  effective singing. The plosives used in beatboxing require abdominal support and this helps
  pupils find their lower support required for singing in performance, further enhancing their
  understanding of their voice as an instrument.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2664-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2664-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2664-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2664-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2664-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2664-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2664-7 ;
  curric:id "2664"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.804425Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-music-over-time-and-in-different-places ,
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2670
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Playing together: arranging and rehearsing a fusion performance"@en ;
  curric:slug "playing-together-arranging-and-rehearsing-a-fusion-performance" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils listen to music in which two or more styles have been fused
  together to create something new. They also learn short musical ideas that represent
  different musical genres and combine these as part of an ensemble."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils now have ample experience being part of an instrumental and vocal
  ensemble, playing tuned and untuned accompaniments, using syncopation and polyrhythms, and
  playing within various styles of music. They have also learnt strategies for effective
  ensemble practice. Now, they are ready to combine all of this learning, creating a fusion
  ensemble piece and further developing their strategies for effective practice. Pupils can
  take this learning of combining musical styles into their theme and variation composition
  unit.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2670-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2670-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2670-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2670-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2670-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2670-6 ;
  curric:id "2670"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.141459Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-music-over-time-and-in-different-places ,
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-2673
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Singing for performance: conveying emotion and character through performance"@en ;
  curric:slug "singing-for-performance-conveying-emotion-and-character-through-performance" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop their vocal technique and perform songs with a
  harmony line. They learn to rehearse songs to a performance standard and evaluate their
  singing, ensuring that they are able to convey the style of each song through an accurate,
  confident and responsive performance."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on performance skills from prior units, pupils are encouraged to
  draw together their singing skills of accurate intonation, their ability to hold a second
  part and their understanding of how the lyrics should be delivered to achieve an effective
  performance. They have also learnt vocal techniques that allow them to look after and warm up
  their voice effectively. Pupils will utilise this and prior learning of the use of musical
  elements such as tempo and dynamics to create an effective performance.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2673-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2673-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2673-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2673-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2673-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2673-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2673-7 ;
  curric:id "2673"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.169346Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-our-singing-voice ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance .

oakcurric:unit-2648
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Start with playing: adding percussive layers to build to texture in our songs"@en ;
  curric:slug "start-with-playing-adding-percussive-layers-to-build-to-texture-in-our-songs" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore texture by adding untuned percussion layers to songs
  and chants. Using repeated rhythms, pupils will develop their sense of pulse and accuracy
  of rhythm. They will identify rhythmic ostinati in listening examples and begin to
  describe texture."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, we continue to see the importance of developing and
  internalising a secure sense of pulse for successful music-making. Pupils combine their
  knowledge of pulse, beat, and rhythm to create rhythmic layers under songs. We build on
  pupils' previous experience of singing with a simple rhythmic ostinato as the second part,
  moving these additional layers onto untuned percussion. Pupils rehearse each layer of the
  piece separately, developing their understanding of how to practise and rehearse effectively
  for future ensemble units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2648-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2648-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2648-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2648-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2648-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2648-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2648-7 ;
  curric:id "2648"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.327747Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance .

oakcurric:unit-2650
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and Create: notating and performing using rhythm grids"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-notating-and-performing-using-rhythm-grids" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores composing rhythmic patterns through the use of rhythm grids.
  Pupils are inspired by exciting percussive performances and work in groups to create and
  perform their own challenging rhythmic patterns."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit continues our exploration of different types of notation, moving
  from the use of images and manipulatives through graphic scores, the introduction of pitch on
  the musical stave, and now rhythm grids to represent percussive rhythms. In this composition
  unit, pupils will build on their ability to play rhythmic ostinati and be part of an
  ensemble. Rehearsing in groups will improve their ability to keep in time with each other.
  Practising and playing in this way will develop their musical skills in preparation for their
  next Playing Together unit.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2650-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2650-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2650-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2650-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2650-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2650-6 ;
  curric:id "2650"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.448743Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music ,
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-2660
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Singing for performance: discovering different ways to sing in harmony"@en ;
  curric:slug "singing-for-performance-discovering-different-ways-to-sing-in-harmony" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit celebrates the many ways of singing in harmony, utilising rounds,
  partner songs, melodic and rhythmic ostinato and counter melody to create layers of sound.
  Through short examples, pupils discover how pitches can be combined to make pleasing
  harmonies."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """By this unit, pupils have had plentiful opportunities to sing in parts,
  beginning with echo and call and response and moving on to rhythmic ostinato, partner songs,
  and rounds. In this unit, we add melodic ostinato and countermelody to their repertoire of
  accompaniment types. They are also skilled at holding an instrumental accompaniment whilst
  singing. By this point, the pupils are ready to hold various parts in a song and are able to
  begin some early analysis of how different pitches fit together.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2660-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2660-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2660-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2660-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2660-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2660-6 ;
  curric:id "2660"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.453640Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-our-singing-voice ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance .

oakcurric:unit-2652
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and Create: major pentatonic melodies"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-composing-a-pentatonic-melody-using-a-simplified-stave" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils discover the power and versatility of the pentatonic scale. Pupils learn
  that pentatonic music is found around the world and sing pentatonic songs from every
  continent. A three-line simplified stave is used for notation. Pupils play and compose
  pentatonic melodies on tuned percussion."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit expands the studied toneset with the introduction of ‘re’ to
  ‘do, re, mi, so, la’ - one example of a pentatonic scale. The pupils, comfortable with
  finding do, mi, so, la on tuned percussion and on the simplified stave are able to add ‘re’
  into their repertoire and compose and perform using this new pitch. Later in 'Compose and
  Create' units, pupils will expand their toneset further to the major pentachord (first five
  notes in the major scale) followed by the minor pentachord (first five notes in the minor
  scale).""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2652-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2652-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2652-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2652-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2652-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2652-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2652-7 ;
  curric:id "2652"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.455940Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music ,
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-2665
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and Create: composing a minor melody on a stave"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-composing-a-minor-melody-on-a-stave" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn songs and listen to music that has a minor tonality.
  Pupils learn the toneset for the minor pentachord (la, ti, do, re, mi) and use this to
  compose a minor melody. An analysis of Benjamin Britten’s Old Abram Brown inspires the
  shaping of the pupils' compositions."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Prior to this unit, pupils have sung songs, heard music and composed using
  the major key, an Indian raag and a pentatonic scale. Pupils have also sung songs and heard
  music in the minor key. They are now in a position to play and compose using a third
  five-note scale, the minor pentachord. The pupils will use their knowledge of these different
  scales and tonalities when improvising in later units and composing variations on a theme.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2665-8 ;
  curric:id "2665"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.458148Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2659
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and Create: composing a major melody on a stave"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-composing-a-major-melody-on-a-stave" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore the tonality of a major melody through listening to a
  range of music. Pupils learn the major pentachord, the first five notes of the scale, on
  tuned percussion. They use this new scale to compose and notate short melodies."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """By this unit pupils have developed their ability to read, sing, play,
  notate and compose melodies that use the pentatonic scale (do, re, mi, so, la). Now we
  introduce the note 'fa' in order to play and compose using the major pentachord (do, re, mi,
  fa, so). Previously pupils have sung and added melodic accompaniment to songs in the major
  key. In this unit, pupils understand the notes used for the melody. They deepen their ability
  to read and notate using simplified staff notation. In future units, pupils will sing, play
  and compose music using the minor pentachord and minor pentatonic.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2659-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2659-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2659-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2659-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2659-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2659-6 ;
  curric:id "2659"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.462547Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2661
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Sing, play, perform: adding tuned accompaniment to part-singing"@en ;
  curric:slug "sing-play-perform-adding-tuned-accompaniment-to-part-singing" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit focuses on adding vocal and instrumental layers to songs. Pupils
  rehearse contrasting songs in parts and become confident holding the pitch and pulse of a
  line before layering this into four and five part textures with added tuned percussion
  accompaniments."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """By this unit, pupils have sung a range of songs with second parts and are
  able to hold a melodic ostinato and a second melodic line. In this unit we develop this
  further by singing songs in two parts whilst also performing simple accompaniments on tuned
  percussion. Pupils will apply previously taught effective rehearsal strategies when
  practising and performing songs in this unit. This will support pupils' future ensemble work
  in which they will begin to layer repetitive cells and contrasting and syncopated rhythms.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2661-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2661-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2661-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2661-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2661-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2661-6 ,
