    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2651
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Playing together: building texture with melody, drone and ostinato"@en ;
  curric:slug "playing-together-building-texture-with-melody-drone-and-ostinato" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, we build the texture in our songs by adding a drone and melodic
  ostinato. Our focus is on how we rehearse and play together as an ensemble. The songs and
  instrumental accompaniments are taught through listening, practising and memorising."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils' ability to feel the pulse while playing and
  singing. Pupils have experience of accompanying a song using untuned percussion. This is
  developed, with pupils accompanying using simple repeated melodic phrases while singing at
  the same time. The toneset for our accompaniments consolidates earlier learning of do, mi,
  so, and la. Throughout this unit, pupils continue to develop their understanding of how to
  practise and rehearse effectively.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2651-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2651-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2651-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2651-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2651-5 ;
  curric:id "2651"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.513577Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance .

oakcurric:unit-2657
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and Create: improvising within Hindustani classical music"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-improvising-within-hindustani-classical-music" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the three main components of Hindustani classical music. Pupils
  hear rhythmic patterns played on the tabla drums and learn how to recite a taal using the
  spoken mnemonic syllables (bols). They create texture by adding an improvised raag using
  five notes, and finally add a drone."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils build on their ability to add layers of sound and their
  understanding of texture is deepened. The effective use of drones is revisited which supports
  their growing understanding of harmony. This unit incorporates more independent group work
  which offers an increased level of autonomy. Pupils improvise on tuned percussion using an
  expanding toneset. By using improvisation, pupils learn that music isn’t always fixed or
  final. This freedom supports creative composition in later units. Pupils deepen their
  understanding that music can be notated in different ways.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2657-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2657-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2657-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2657-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2657-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2657-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2657-7 ;
  curric:id "2657"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.569554Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-music-over-time-and-in-different-places ,
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2655
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Start with playing: adding layers to major and minor songs"@en ;
  curric:slug "start-with-playing-adding-layers-to-major-and-minor-songs" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the different sounds and feelings associated with major and
  minor tonality explicitly. The pupils sing a variety of songs, some in a major key and
  some in a minor key. They use pitched percussion instruments to add different
  accompaniments to these."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, we explicitly name songs and listening examples that use the
  major or minor key. From their experience of hearing and singing previous major, minor and
  pentatonic music, pupils are able to identify the tonality. We build on prior skills of
  playing drone and ostinato alongside a song with more complex repeated patterns. Pupils will
  learn to move their ostinato from the major key to the minor key. The first five notes of the
  major and minor keys will be consolidated in later 'Compose and Create' units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2655-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2655-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2655-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2655-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2655-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2655-6 ;
  curric:id "2655"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.651104Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-our-singing-voice ,
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble .

oakcurric:unit-2658
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Playing together: effective rehearsing as part of an ensemble"@en ;
  curric:slug "playing-together-effective-rehearsing-as-part-of-an-ensemble" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, we explore effective ensemble rehearsal. Professional ensembles
  share their secrets for success when practising alone, in small groups and as a wider
  ensemble. Effective rehearsal strategies are then explicitly taught to the pupils and
  developed in our ensemble piece."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """By this unit, pupils can perform successfully as a group, adding layers to
  an ensemble piece. They have explored how varying dynamics or tempo can enhance a performance
  and can read simple notation. In this unit, the focus is on how successful rehearsing can
  improve performance. By focusing on this, pupils can begin to identify what aspects of their
  performance they can improve, such as correcting rhythm, accuracy of intonation or
  maintaining a steady pulse as a part of an ensemble. This deepened study of rehearsal
  techniques will guide the pupils' practice in later units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2658-8 ;
  curric:id "2658"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.756374Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2649
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Singing together: how songs are used in communities"@en ;
  curric:slug "singing-together-how-songs-are-used-in-communities" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils learn that singing often draws communities together to tell stories,
  comment on history, share happy or sad times and to worship. Through rehearsing and
  performing a range of songs, pupils explore how different songs capture different
  emotions."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit broadens the pupils' vocal repertoire by exploring different
  ways people sing together. This develops the pupils' understanding of how and why we sing,
  moving on from how singing makes us feel and how singing can help us achieve a task. Through
  this unit, we continue to teach the importance of warming up the voice and body, and we
  introduce songs and games that will develop the pupils' vocal technique, focusing on a wider
  vocal range, clearer articulation and more authentic expression.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2649-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2649-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2649-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2649-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2649-5 ;
  curric:id "2649"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.812698Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-our-singing-voice ,
    oakcurric:thread-music-over-time-and-in-different-places ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance .

oakcurric:unit-2654
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Singing for performance: holding a second part in rounds and partner songs"@en ;
  curric:slug "singing-for-performance-holding-a-second-part-in-rounds-and-partner-songs" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit brings together a diverse range of songs chosen to enable successful
  singing in two simple parts. Through listening and singing, pupils learn how canon,
  specifically rounds and partner songs, are used to build layers of sound in songs."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils have previously learnt how to add a second layer to their music
  through rhythmic ostinato. Now, they are introduced to a melodic second line through the form
  of rounds and partner songs. Using a mixture of familiar and new songs, pupils gain another
  understanding of how texture can be built in a song. Pupils are embedding the skill of
  feeling the pulse by hearing how their vocal line fits into the structure of a round or
  partner song. Understanding how lines of a song can be layered provides an initial experience
  of singing in harmony.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2654-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2654-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2654-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2654-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2654-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2654-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2654-7 ;
  curric:id "2654"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.831706Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-our-singing-voice ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance .

oakcurric:unit-2669
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and rehearse: improvising with the minor pentatonic scale"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-rehearse-improvising-over-a-three-chord-structure" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils listen to improvisation in jazz ensembles. Using the minor
  pentatonic scale on pitched percussion, they learn a minor pentatonic melody and practise
  tools to guide successful improvisation including repetition and sequencing."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, we introduce a fourth five-note scale, with the pupils now
  having learnt the major pentatonic, major and minor pentachords and now the minor pentatonic.
  Having a sound study of tuned percussion behind them, they are now in a position to improvise
  effectively and fluently over a chord sequence. Improvising whilst considering repetition,
  balance and sequencing will give pupils the foundations they need in the later notated
  composition unit.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2669-8 ;
  curric:id "2669"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.833590Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-music-over-time-and-in-different-places ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-creating-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-2666
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Singing for performance: syncopation in songs"@en ;
  curric:slug "singing-for-performance-discovering-different-vocal-timbres" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to the term syncopation through adding syncopated
  rhythms to songs. Pupils learn how to feel the offbeats through movement and experience
  how straight rhythms and syncopated rhythms feel different. Syncopated rhythm patterns
  form an accompaniment to a range of songs."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces pupils to the term syncopation through adding
  syncopated rhythms to songs. Pupils learn how to feel the offbeats through movement and
  experience how straight rhythms and syncopated rhythms feel different. Syncopated rhythm
  patterns form an accompaniment to a range of songs.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2666-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2666-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2666-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2666-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2666-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2666-6 ;
  curric:id "2666"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.839349Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
