    oakcurric:thread-music-over-time-and-in-different-places ,
    oakcurric:thread-practising-and-preparing-for-a-performance ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-2667
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Sing, play, perform: accompanying songs with polyrhythms"@en ;
  curric:slug "sing-play-perform-syncopation-in-songs" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores different rhythm patterns from around the world. Through body
  percussion pupils play contrasting styles of rhythms and transfer these onto untuned
  percussion. They play one rhythm against another, building up layers of sound whilst
  maintaining a secure sense of pulse."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils will develop their ability to layer multiple rhythms,
  building on previous units in which they layered different parts in songs, instrumental
  accompaniments and composed ostinati. The pupils utilise previously studied rehearsal skills
  and reflect on previous learning around effective ensemble practice, building on these
  rehearsal skills for a more effective performance. Pupils are introduced to the term
  polyrhythms.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2667-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2667-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2667-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2667-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2667-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2667-6 ;
  curric:id "2667"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.021347Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-playing-together-in-an-ensemble ,
    oakcurric:thread-notating-and-sharing-music .

oakcurric:unit-3892
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and create: cosmic programme music"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-cosmic-programme-music" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils are introduced to the term, programme music. They study the
  programme music symphonic work, Deep Field, by Eric Whitacre and use this as their
  inspiration for composing, considering structuring around the golden ratio and the use of
  small music ideas called golden bricks."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils are given the opportunity to develop their creative music skills
  further, composing and improvising in a way that offers plenty of freedom of expression.
  Pupils can use their composition skills developed in other lower key stage two units
  alongside their working knowledge of the musical elements to create programme music as part
  of an ensemble with greater freedom than before. Due to the freedom of composition suggested
  in the lessons, this unit can be placed at any point across the key stage, with the
  compositional, performance and ensemble outcomes adjusted accordingly.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3892-9 ;
  curric:id "3892"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.328029Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-2 .

oakcurric:unit-3896
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Compose and create: nature documentary inspired film scores"@en ;
  curric:slug "compose-and-create-nature-documentary-inspired-film-scores" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils are introduced to the term, film music. They study many
  examples of film music composed for the BBC nature documentaries Planet Earth II and
  Planet Earth III and use these as their inspiration for composing their own film scores."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils are given the opportunity to develop their creative music skills
  further, composing and improvising in a way that offers plenty of freedom of expression and
  the chance to explore technology in music. Pupils can use their composition skills developed
  in other upper key stage two units, alongside their working knowledge of the musical elements
  to create film music with greater freedom than before. Due to the freedom of composition
  suggested in the lessons, this unit can be placed at any point across the key stage, with the
  compositional outcomes adjusted accordingly.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3896-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3896-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3896-3 ,
